The '''Loi du 20 décembre 1988 relative à la protection des personnes qui se prêtent à des recherches biomédicales''', also known as the '''Loi Huriet''' or '''Loi Huriet-Sérusclat''', is a [[French civil law]] to establish the regulation of those working in [[biomedical research]], and to formalise the [[status quo]] of [[bioethics]]. It was proposed under the second government of [[Michel Rocard]] ([[Parti socialiste (France)|Parti socialiste]]) six months after the [[French legislative election, 1988]]. It was the first French law that put [[clinical trial]]s on a firm legal footing.

== First statute ==
An appendix, IIb, to the French civil code on [[Public Health]], established the [[Comité consultatif de protection des personnes dans la recherche biomédicale]] (CCPPRB), later succeeded by the [[Comités de protection des personnes]] (CPP). Its ambit, defined in Article 15, established in law the notion of a {{lang|fr|consentement éclairé}} (a "Clear [[consent]]", perhaps similar to the [[Clean hands doctrine]] in [[common law]]), and established penalties for breaking the law.

The common name {{lang|fr|[[Loi Sérusclat-Huriet]]}}, and abbreviated variations such as {{lang|fr|[[Loi Huriet]]}} and {{lang|fr|[[Loi Sérusclat]]}}, come from the names of the nominator and seconder in the [[Senate (France)|French senate]], [[Claude Huriet]] ([[Union pour la démocratie française|Centrist]]) and [[Franck Sérusclat]] ([[Parti socialiste (France)|Socialist]]).

==Evolution==
As cases came to court with the usual [[jurisprudence]],<ref group="Note">A French judge has far more investigative powers than those in [[Common law]] jurisdictions.</ref> public perception of the importance of [[bioethics]] and other [[European Union law]], have supplemented the powers made under the original regulatory framework, such as {{lang-fr|[[Loi n°94-653 du 29 juillet 1994, relative au respect du corps humain]]}} ("Law of 29 July 1994, Respect of the human body"), which defined the legal notion of [[dignity]], and {{lang|fr|[[Loi du 4 mars 2002 relative aux droits des malades et à la qualité du système de santé]]}} ("Law of 4 March 2002, Patient rights and the quality of health system").

