{{Infobox person | image = Prvoslav Vujčić photo article final copy 5.jpg | caption = Vujcic in 2006 | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1960|07|20}} | birth_place = [[Požarevac]], Serbia{{Cref2|a}} | residence = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] | birth_name = Prvoslav Vujčić | occupation = Author | partner = | years_active = | spouse = | children = 4 | parents = | family = | website = | signature = }} '''Prvoslav Vujcic''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Првослав Вујчић}}, {{IPA-sr|př̩ʋoslaʋ ʋûːjtʃitɕ|sr}}; born 20 July 1960) is a Canadian writer, poet, translator, columnist and [[aphorism|aphorist]] of Serbian origin.<ref>''Vesti'', May 2007, Prvoslav Vujčić začetnik novog poetskog stila {{sr icon}}</ref> He has been described as one of the most prominent writers of Serbian origin.<ref name="Svaki Srbin roman za sebe">{{cite web |url=http://www.srpskadijaspora.info/svaki-srbin-roman-za-sebe/ |author=''Srpska dijaspora'' |title=Svaki Srbin roman za sebe |accessdate=25 October 2017 |date=24 February 2004}}</ref><ref name="RTS">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n5KwaR0LyFQ |author=[[Radio Television of Serbia]] |title=Intervju, RTS – Prvoslav Vujčić, književnik |accessdate=2 December 2015 |year=February 2004}}</ref><ref name="Migrating Memories 2010. pp. 306">''Migrating Memories: Central Europe in Canada Volume I – Literary Anthology''. CEACS. 2010. pp. 306–308. {{ISBN|978-86-7746-233-8}}.</ref>
==Life== Vujcic was born on 20 July 1960 in the [[Southern and Eastern Serbia|eastern]] [[Serbia]]n city of [[Požarevac]] to father Jefrem and mother Nadežda and it was in Požarevac that he completed his [[primary education|elementary education]].<ref name="Urban Book Circle">{{cite web |url=https://www.urbanbookcircle.com/prvoslav-ldquopearserdquo-vujcic.html |publisher=Urban Book Circle |title=Prvoslav Vujčić biography |accessdate=27 July 2013 |date=16 May 2013 }}</ref> In 1975, Vujcic won the Zmaj Award (awarded annually by the [[Association of Writers of Serbia]] for the best book of the year) for his collection of poetry titled ''Pesnik i pesma'' – the award was presented to him by [[Desanka Maksimović]].<ref name="ReferenceA">''[[Večernje novosti]]'' (31 March 2007). "Rodoljubive pesme, pg. 26" {{sr icon}}.</ref> In 1977, he visited Canada and the [[United States]] for the first time where he met one of his literary influences [[Charles Bukowski]]. Vujcic then read and presented his poetry with Bukowski on tour for fourteen days in 1977.<ref name="The Canada Gazette 1989">''The Canada Gazette: La Gazette du Canada'', Volume 123, Issue 1, Part 1 (in English & French). Queen's Printer. 1989.</ref> Vujcic completed his ''[[matura]]'' and graduated from the [[Požarevac Gymnasium]] in 1979. In the late 1970s and early 1980s, he was the leader of the Požarevac section of the [[Grobari]], the supporters group of [[FK Partizan|Partizan Belgrade]].<ref name="Migrating Memories 2010. pp. 306"/> In 1983, Vujcic wrote a book of poetry titled ''Razmišljanja jednog leša'' which was banned by the [[League of Communists of Serbia|Communist government]] in [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] by court order in 1983.<ref name="Ginsberg, Whitman, Banned Poetry and a Supermarket in California ">{{cite web |url=http://www.barnonegroup.com/2016/10/ginsberg-whitman-banned-poetry-and.html |author=Bar None Group |title=Ginsberg, Whitman, Banned Poetry and a Supermarket in California |accessdate=17 May 2017 |date=4 October 2016 |language=English}}</ref> In [[1984 in literature|1984]], Vujcic was [[Political prisoners in Yugoslavia|imprisoned]] in [[Tuzla]] for seven days (for his writing and criticizing of Yugoslavia's communist regime) where he wrote his second book of poetry titled ''Kastriranje vetra'' which was also banned by the Communist government.<ref name="Canadian Dust">{{cite web |url=http://www.arhiv.rs/novinska-clanak/danas/2004/2/7/3B03BBEC53A4C6E7C1256E3300766B43/kanadska-prasina |author=''[[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]]'' |title=Kanadska prašina |accessdate=23 September 2015 |date=7 February 2004 |language=Serbian}}</ref><ref name="Otadžbina na Gembl aveniji">{{cite web |url=http://www.arhiv.rs/novinska-clanak/politika/2004/3/28/B4982374C7526F4CC1256E65004B277C/otadzbina-na-gembl-aveniji |author=''[[Politika]]'' |title=Otadžbina na Gembl aveniji |accessdate=23 September 2015 |date=28 March 2004 |language=Serbian}}</ref><ref name="Nezavisne Novine ref">{{cite web |url=http://www.novine.ca/starevesti/Zajednica/srpska_zajednica104.html |author=''Nezavisne Novine'' |title=Promocija knjiga Prvoslava Vujčića |accessdate=2017-10-18 |date=2004-04-27 |language=Serbian |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913182939/http://www.novine.ca/starevesti/Zajednica/srpska_zajednica104.html |archivedate=2017-09-13 |df= }}</ref>
In January 1987, Vujcic moved to Canada.<ref>''Reč naroda'' (issue #1927, pg. 9; 3 February 1987). "Portreti – Prvoslav Vujčić – Reč kao osnov" {{sr icon}}</ref> Upon arrival in Canada, he helped raise funds for the construction of the [[Church of Saint Sava]] in [[Belgrade]] and the [[Živojin Mišić]] monument in [[Mionica]].<ref name="Migrating Memories 2010. pp. 306"/> On 28 June 1989, Vujcic helped organize the 600th Anniversary Ceremony commemorating the [[Battle of Kosovo]] throughout Canada.<ref name="Migrating Memories 2010. pp. 306"/> The ''[[Canada Gazette]]'' wrote about Vujcic and his beginnings in Canada in a 1989 edition.<ref name="The Canada Gazette 1989"/> In 1992, he founded the United Serbs FC soccer club for which he and [[Mike Stojanović]] played (as a child, Vujcic played soccer in the youth categories of FK Železničar Požarevac).<ref>''Srpske novine'' (24 September 1992). "FK Ujedinjeni Srbi, Serbian News #2607, pg. 14" (in Serbian)</ref> During this period, Vujcic was a contributor to Serbian magazine ''[[Pogledi]]''. In 1999, he was one of the organizers of the Toronto-based demonstrations against the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|bombing of Serbia and Montenegro]]. In terms of the Serbian diaspora, the demonstrations lasted all 78 days only in Toronto.<ref name="Serbia 2005. pp. 47">''U čast pisaca iz rasejanja'' (in Serbian). Ministry of Diaspora of the Republic of Serbia. 2005. pp. 47–48. {{ISBN|86-906685-0-0}}.</ref>
Vujcic is a member of the [[Association of Writers of Serbia]], the [[Royal Canadian Legion]], the [[Canadian Association of Journalists]], the [[Srpska književna zadruga|Serbian Literary Society]], the [[Association of Writers of Republika Srpska]] and the US-based International Association of Writers.<ref>''[[Borba (newspaper)|Borba]]'' (9 April 2005). "Pisac je livac: Prvoslav Vujčić, pg. 18" {{sr icon}}.</ref> In 2007, the International Association of Writers<ref name="Migrating Memories 2010. pp. 306"/> named him a Poetry Ambassador of the United States.<ref name="Migrating Memories 2010. pp. 306"/><ref name="ReferenceA"/> He is also an honourable member of the Desanka Maksimović Serbian Canadian Association. Vujcic is featured in the book ''Moždana veza sa Srbijom, 100 dragulja srpskog rasejanja'' (''Brain Connection with Serbia, 100 Jewels of the Serbian Diaspora)'' by Radivoje Petrović, PhD. The book features the "one hundred most-known Serbs throughout the world-wide Serbian diaspora."<ref>''Moždana veza sa Srbijom, 100 dragulja srpskog rasejanja'' (in Serbian). Global Puls Beograd & Serbian Unity Congress, San Francisco. 2005. pp. 286–288.</ref> He was also featured on the cover of the Ministry of Diaspora of the Republic of Serbia book called ''U čast pisaca iz rasejanja / In honour of writers in the diaspora'' in which literary critics [[Miodrag Perišić]] and [[Čedomir Mirković]] said that "Vujcic is one of the most significant living Serbian poets and dissidents."<ref name="Serbia 2005. pp. 47"/>
He is the founder of the Urban Book Circle, based in Canada.<ref name="Urban Book Circle"/>
