Abbé '''Raoul Maurice Jean Carton''' (1879&nbsp;– 7 July 1934) was a [[French people|French]] [[French philosophy|philosopher]].

==Life==
Raoul Maurice Jean Carton was born in [[Blois]], [[France]], in 1879. A [[Catholicism in France|Catholic]] [[Catholic priest|priest]], he became professor of philosophy at [[Collège Stanislas de Paris|Stanislas College]] (''{{lang|fr|Collège Stanislas}}'') and the [[Institut Catholique de Paris|Catholic Institute]] (''{{lang|fr|Institut Catholique}}'') in Paris. He particularly focused on the work of [[Roger Bacon]], who had been considered a lone scientific genius by 19th century scholarship but whom Carton and others labored to return to his medieval context. He died in [[Paris]] on 7 July 1934.

